Dutch filmmaker Theo van Gogh, known for his controversial views on Islam, was tragically murdered in broad daylight while cycling in Amsterdam.
His film "Submission" sparked outrage in the Muslim community for its portrayal of women in Islamic culture.
The suspect, a 26-year-old with Dutch-Moroccan nationality, had ties to extremist Muslims.
The assassination led to a national outcry for justice and unity.
Van Gogh's outspoken criticism of Islam ultimately cost him his life, leaving the Netherlands grappling with questions of tolerance and division.
The Dutch government condemned the act and called for calm amidst the turmoil.
